    <h2>A small root</h2>
    <pre><code>svc := partial.NewService(&partial.Config{
    Connector: connector.NewHTMX(nil),
    FS:        os.DirFS("templates"),
})

layout := svc.NewLayout().
    Set(partial.NewID("content", "pages/home.gohtml")).
    Wrap(partial.NewID("layout", "layout.gohtml"))

_ = layout.WriteWithRequest(r.Context(), w, r)</code></pre>

    <p>The rest of this site is rendered by that same pattern. The navigation, sidebar, examples, and error sections are all partials.</p>

    <h2>What go-partial is optimizing for</h2>
    <ul>
        <li>Keep templates as normal <code>html/template</code> files.</li>
        <li>Let the server decide what a target, action, or selected partial means.</li>
        <li>Make repeated fragments explicit without requiring a new component language.</li>
        <li>Return useful HTML even when one section fails during development.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Integrates with</h2>
    <p>go-partial is designed to sit beside packages such as <code>go-translator</code>, <code>go-form</code>, <code>go-importmap</code>, and <code>go-router</code>. The renderer stays focused on partial trees and response behavior while the application stack handles routing, assets, translation, and forms.</p>
</article>
